    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:7d1489ad-5541-4cc3-a1c2-79d6d8b47054",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 17-year-old high school junior who appears his stated age, dressed in clean but wrinkled clothes with limited attention to grooming compared with his peers. He has a thin build, slouched posture, and tends to avoid prolonged eye contact. During conversation he speaks softly and slowly, often pausing before answering. His facial expression is subdued, and he reports feeling “tired all the time” and “not interested in much lately.” Over the past 2 months he has become increasingly withdrawn, spending more time alone in his room and less time engaging with friends.\n\nHe lives with his mother, stepfather, and younger sister in a suburban apartment and previously enjoyed playing basketball, gaming online with friends, and drawing. Recently, however, he has stopped attending informal basketball games and has let several school assignments pile up. He describes difficulty concentrating in class, low motivation, early-morning awakening, and a reduced appetite with mild unintentional weight loss. Teachers have noticed a decline in participation and grades. He denies alcohol or illicit drug use, though he occasionally consumes energy drinks late at night while trying to finish homework.\n\nSocially, {patientName} has a small but established friend group, though he has been ignoring texts and declining invitations. His mother reports that he is more irritable at home, especially when asked about school performance. He feels guilty that he is “disappointing everyone” and has become pessimistic about his future. He has no psychotic symptoms and no clear history of manic episodes. He is not currently in a romantic relationship and describes feeling isolated even when around other people.\n\nFunctionally, his depressive symptoms are affecting school attendance, academic performance, sleep routine, and family relationships. He spends hours scrolling on his phone without enjoyment and often naps after school, which worsens nighttime sleep. He has begun seeing the school counselor after concerns were raised about his persistent low mood and loss of interest. He is cooperative with evaluation but minimizes his distress at times, a pattern common in adolescents who are uncomfortable discussing emotional symptoms openly."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:54c49ee4-1129-4e67-a00d-d2ac7eb0eb55",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has no major chronic medical illness and no prior psychiatric hospitalization. His immunizations are up to date. Over the last year, increasing academic pressure and conflict with his biological father over inconsistent contact have contributed to emotional stress. His mother notes that he became noticeably more withdrawn after changing schools 8 months ago. There is no known history of manic symptoms, psychosis, eating disorder behavior, or substance misuse. He denies sexual activity. \n\nPast medical history is notable for mild intermittent asthma in childhood, now rarely symptomatic, and seasonal allergic rhinitis. He has never undergone surgery other than a simple laceration repair in childhood. He has not previously taken antidepressants. He saw a pediatrician once 6 weeks ago for fatigue and headaches; no acute medical issue was found, and he was advised to improve sleep habits. \n\nLifestyle factors include irregular sleep, frequent late-night screen exposure, reduced physical activity, and skipping breakfast several days per week. He previously participated in school basketball but quit this season because of low energy and poor motivation. Family members report he is spending much less time outdoors and rarely socializing. He currently receives informal support from the school counselor, and a safety assessment is indicated because adolescents with depressive symptoms may underreport suicidal thoughts."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
